      "title": "README",
      "properties": {},
      "widgets_values": [
        "[Github](https://github.com/stuttlepress) | [CivitAI](https://civitai.com/user/__Bob__) \n***\n*You're free to do whatever you want with this workflow, but it makes me feel good when you give me credit. Redistributing it without attribution is kind of lame.*\n\n***\n\n# How to Use This Workflow\n\n## 1. Install the [*ComfyUI-Wan-VACE-Prep*](https://github.com/stuttlepress/ComfyUI-Wan-VACE-Prep) node pack.\n\nIf you already have the package, make sure you're at **v1.0.16** or higher.\n\nIt's a tiny package with no dependencies, so it is very unlikely to break your system, if you worry about such things.\n\nIf you don't already have the node, you can open the Manager and install it either from the *Missing Nodes* section, or search for **Wan VACE Prep**.\n\n## 2. Select models appropriate for your system\n- Select your VACE and other models in the *Load* group. \n- Select or disable speedup loras.\n\n## 3. Load your video.\nDrag and drop your input video onto the **Load Video** node or use the *choose file to upload* UI to select it.\n\n\n## 4. Run *just the VACE Outpaint Prep node* to populate it with your video.  \nDo one of the following:\n   * Click the node, then click the blue **Run** button in the icon bar that appears above it (not the Run button at the top of the ComfyUI window).\n   * If you have [rgthree](https://github.com/rgthree/rgthree-comfy) installed, right click the node and select *Queue Selected Output Nodes (rgthree)*.  \n\nAfter your video has loaded, you can scrub through it with the **frame** slider. This has no effect on output.\n## 5. Select output.  \n   * Adjust the selection box to frame your desired output. Red areas will be generated by the VACE model. \n   * Confirm **output resolution** matches your target.\n## 7. Prompt.\nEnter a prompt describing the scene, especially what's in the outpainted area.\n## 8. Run the workflow.\nThe outpainted video will be placed in your ComfyUI *output* directory, named something like `outpainted_0001.mp4`\n"
      ],
      "color": "#232",
      "bgcolor": "#353"
    }
